We take first the categorical variables.

cox_3loc<- coxph(Surv(total_lived, censored) ~ location, data= datos_field_lab)

In this first model, it takes as a reference the Semi Urban area (location =1); location Urban (Palafolls) has a hazard ratio of 0.79534 (<1), which means that being in the Urban location reduces 0.79534 the risk of death. CI 95% is [0.6925-0.9135], which means association at 5% level. In Laboratory location occurs the same; being in the Laboratory reduces the risk of death compared to the reference in 0.44581. We see that is even more significative than the Urban Location. CI 95% is [0.3891-0.5108], which means association at 5% level. Conclussion: in Semi Urban location we have more risk of death than in Urban location or Laboratory.

Cox model of method of capture (only data from the field, since theres no method of capture in the lab); it takes HL as reference of the method of capture; we see that BG method has a hazard ratio of 1.56897, which means that being captured for a BG-trap instead of HL increases the risk of death 1.56897 times. COX REGRESSION WITH CONTINUOUS VARIABLES: WEATHER

Now we are going to prepare the dataframe: 1. We need to have as much rows as days lived for each mosquito, to be able to analyze the fluctuation of the weather in all their lives, not only the day of start. 2. We need to calculate photoperiod.

With this, we will start doing Cox models with all the variables, categorical and continuous.

df <- read_excel("datos_field.xlsx", col_types = c("numeric",

clima$start_date <- as.character(as.Date(clima$start_date, format = '%Y-%m-%d'))

new_df <- do.call('rbind', lapply(seq_len(nrow(df)), function(id){
  tmp <- do.call('rbind', replicate(df$total_lived[id],
                                    df[id, ], simplify = FALSE))
  tmp$start_date <- format(seq(tmp$start_date[1], by = 'day',
                               length.out = nrow(tmp)), '%Y-%m-%d')
  tmp
}))

vars <- c('maxtemperature', 'meantemperature', 'mintemperature', 'maxrh', 'minrh', 'meanrh')

First of all, as we want to be sure that the categorical variables dont influence the others, we want to separate the dataframe in 4 parts: 1) Only data from BG-traps 2) Only data from HL 3) Only data from Semi-Urban area 4) Only data from Urban area

Once we do this, we will check one by one which variables are affecting (and how) to the survival. Then, we will add them into a complete model and we will see if they change.

data_hl<- subset(new_df, method=="HL")

In model 1 (only minimum RH is added) we get a hazard ratio of 0.9979 (p-value <0.05). That means that an increase of 1 in min RH produces a decrease in the risk of death of 0.9979782. CI95% [0.9966-0.9993] doesnt include 1, so there is significative association at 5% level.

In model 2 (only mean RH is added) we get a hazard ratio of 0.9968 (p-value<0.05). An increase of 1 ud in meanRH produces a decrease in the risk of death of 0.9968. CI95%[0.995-0.9985]; it doesnt include 1 (barely) so there is significative association at 5% level.

In model 3 (only max RH is added) we get a hazard ratio of 0.997363 (p-value <0.05). An increase of 1 ud in max Rh produces a decrease in the risk of death of 0.997363. CI95% [0.9952-0.9995]; it doesnt include 1, so there is significative association at 5% level.

In model 4 (we put maxrh and minrh in the model) we get a hazard ratio of 0.9993 in maxrh and 0.9982 in minrh. None of them are significative (in minrh, pvalue very close to be significant). In both of them, CI95% includes 1, so theres no significant association at 5% level.

In model 5 (we put meanrh and minrh) we obtain a hazard ratio of 0.993326 in meanrh and 1.002796 in minrh. We see here that now minrh has a coefficient >1, but it isnt significative (p-value > 0.05). Also the CI95% in minrh includes 1, so theres no significant association at 5% level when this 2 variables are together.

In model 6 (we put maxrh and meanrh), we obtain a hazard ratio of 0.994449 in meanrh and 1.003311 in maxrh. We see that now maxrh has a coefficient >1 , but it isnt significative (p-value >0.05). Also the CI95% in maxrh includes 1, so theres no significant association at 5% level when this 2 variables are together.

In model 7 (we put all the rh); the hazard ratio of maxrh is >1 and significative here (1.011319, p-value <0.05). Also minrh is >1 and significative when the 3 variables are together (1.010431, p-value <0.05). MeanRH remains <1 and significative.

It seems like meanRH is influencing in some way with minRH and maxRH
